{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17613535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17613535"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:36:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:36:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16312"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16312"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9003"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66588"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9003"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16312"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52041"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1456"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"5931"},{"type":"tags","id":"7198"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21427"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21431"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22169"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66588"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with severe vertigo for the past 24 hours. He reports constant room-spinning dizziness and frequent vomiting. His hearing is normal. He had an upper respiratory tract infection caused by \u003Cem\u003EHaemophilus influenzae\u003C/em\u003E two weeks ago which has resolved. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with vital signs within normal limits. He has horizontal nystagmus worse when looking to the left. Otoscopic examination is normal. Weber and Rinne tests demonstrate normal hearing. He has a positive head impulse test to the right.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Benign paroxysmal positional vertigo","Labyrinthitis","Meniere disease","Vestibular neuritis","Migraine"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute onset persistent vertigo without hearing loss, following a recent upper respiratory tract infection. These features are classic for \u003Cstrong\u003Evestibular neuritis\u003C/strong\u003E. Vestibular neuritis is thought to be caused by post-viral inflammation of the vestibular portion of the vestibulocochlear nerve, sparing the cochlear portion which explains the preserved hearing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVestibular neuritis typically presents with acute severe vertigo lasting days to weeks, associated with nystagmus and positive head impulse test, but importantly spares hearing as only the vestibular portion of the eighth cranial nerve is affected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenign paroxysmal positional vertigo\u003C/strong\u003E (BPPV) causes brief episodes of vertigo lasting seconds to minutes, triggered by changes in head position. The persistent nature of this patient\u0027s symptoms makes BPPV unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELabyrinthitis\u003C/strong\u003E involves inflammation of both the vestibular and cochlear portions of the inner ear, resulting in vertigo WITH associated hearing loss, which this patient does not have.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeniere disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with episodic vertigo, fluctuating hearing loss, tinnitus, and aural fullness. The absence of auditory symptoms and the temporal relationship to a recent infection make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E migraine \u003C/strong\u003Eheadache could cause these symptoms, but they would be very unlikely to be so persistent.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vestibular neuritis presents with acute vertigo without hearing loss, often following an upper respiratory tract infection.","Vestibular neuritis is distinguished from labyrinthitis by the absence of hearing loss, as it only affects the vestibular portion of the vestibulocochlear nerve.","Post-viral inflammation is the most common cause of vestibular neuritis."],"references":["Bae CH, Na HG, Choi YS. Current diagnosis and treatment of vestibular neuritis: a narrative review. J Yeungnam Med Sci. 2022 Apr;39(2):81-88. doi: 10.12701/yujm.2021.01228. Epub 2021 Aug 9. PMID: 34411472; PMCID: PMC8913909","Oussoren FK, Schermer TR, Bruintjes TD, Leeuwen RBV. Idiopathic Labyrinthitis: Symptoms, Clinical Characteristics, and Prognosis. J Int Adv Otol. 2023 Nov;19(6):478-484. doi: 10.5152/iao.2023.231096. PMID: 38088320; PMCID: PMC10765229","Barkwill D, Arora R. Labyrinthitis. 2023 Aug 14. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32809341"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52041"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16312"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52041","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52041"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T09:38:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T09:38:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9003"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66588"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}